vectorData.altText: 13) The paper is being pinched between the pad of the thumb and the pad of the index finger. What muscle and nerve are responsible for the action of the thumb?

That's right! The opponens pollicis is responsible for opposition, a movement that only occurs at the 1st carpometacarpal joint. Opponens pollicis is a thenar muscle, and therefore is innervated by the recurrent branch of the median nerve.

Identify, at the base of the fifth digit, the hypothenar muscles. They are intrinsic muscles of the hand dedicated to the fifth digit. Realize that they are responsible for the hypothenar eminence, a surface feature of the medial aspect of the palm     . They are innervated by the ulnar nerve.
